<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This hardly differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ochracea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea ochracea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except in the smaller dimensions of its corolla. It is, however, much more widespread in the Old World Tropics than 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ochracea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea ochracea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="obscura" variety="fragilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea obscura</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">fragilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the type in the concolorous pale yellow colour of the corolla. It is southern African in distribution.
</paragraph>
